    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-01-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-01-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="574"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 822.00/184.]</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 17, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegram of January 2, via Bogotá, regarding closure of ports to commerce.
                    You will state to the Government of Ecuador that this Government must regard
                    proclamations closing ports not in the possession of the regular Government as
                    utterly nugatory unless, and only as long as, such ports are effectively
                    blockaded. State further that this Government reserves on behalf of citizens of
                    the United States, and their vessels and other property, all rights to which
                    they may be found entitled under the law and the facts in any case that may
                    arise. See Moore’s Digest, Sec. 1271, particularly pages 808 et seq., for the
                    general principles of international law applicable to such cases.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
